<!-- aide-orientation-start -->

Your brain is an Obsidian-backed knowledge store. Use `mcp__brain__read_note` to
open files by their brain-relative path. Use `mcp__brain__search_notes` for
keyword queries across every note in the store. The store has four entry-point
artifacts: the coding-playbook index at `coding-playbook/coding-playbook.md`, the
study-playbook navigation guide at `coding-playbook/study-playbook.md`, the
update-playbook maintenance guide at `coding-playbook/update-playbook.md`, and the
research index at `research/research.md`. Start from the relevant entry-point for
your task, follow the references it lists to deepen context, and check those
files' references too. Stay in scope; don't follow references into unrelated topics.

<!-- aide-orientation-end -->

<!-- aide-config-start -->

You are completing the wiring of an Obsidian brain. The required value is the
absolute path to the user's Obsidian vault, to be placed at the last entry of
`mcpServerConfig.args` in `brain.aide`. YAML null at that position is the
unwired-state signal â€” it means the brain path has not yet been filled in.

Argument shape (Obsidian only): `/aide:brain config [<absolute-path>]`.

This flow has two paths that NEVER overlap in the same session: WIRING and
SEEDING. Wiring edits `brain.aide` and runs sync, then STOPS â€” the brain MCP
server only loads at session start, so any newly-wired brain entry is
unreachable until the user restarts Claude Code. Seeding writes the
entry-point artifacts via the brain MCP tools, which only works when the brain
is already wired AND the session has the brain MCP server loaded â€” i.e., on a
run AFTER the wiring restart.

1. **Read `brain.aide` now and quote the last entry of `mcpServerConfig.args`.**
   Open `brain.aide` and locate the final entry in the `mcpServerConfig.args`
   list. Quote the literal value you observe â€” either YAML null (an empty entry,
   written as a bare dash with no value) or a string. **Do not proceed without
   quoting it.** YAML null means un-wired; any string value means already wired.

2. Decide which flow runs:
   - `$ARGUMENTS` non-empty â†’ **WIRING** flow. Use `$ARGUMENTS` as the target
     path (initial wiring or re-point). Proceed to Step 3.
   - `$ARGUMENTS` empty AND last entry is YAML null â†’ **WIRING** flow. Ask the
     user where their vault lives via `AskUserQuestion` with `aide_info.brain.hints`
     as suggestions plus a "Different location" entry. Use the answer as the
     target path. Proceed to Step 3.
   - `$ARGUMENTS` empty AND last entry is a string path â†’ **SEEDING** flow.
     The brain is already wired; skip Steps 3 and 4 entirely and jump to Step 5.

### WIRING flow â€” Steps 3, 4 (then STOP at end of 4)

3. Edit `brain.aide` â€” replace the null at the last entry of `mcpServerConfig.args`
   with the absolute path.

4. **Run sync now via Bash.** Read `.mcp.json["mcpServers"]["aide"]`, take its
   `command` and `args`, append the literal string `"sync"`, and execute the
   resulting command via the Bash tool. Quote the exit code. On non-zero, surface
   stderr and stop. On exit 0:

   **STOP HERE in the WIRING flow.** Do not proceed to Step 5 in the same
   session. The brain MCP server was not loaded at session start (it did not
   exist yet), and sync just wrote the entry; the running session cannot see
   it. Emit this message verbatim and end the flow:

   > Sync wrote the brain entry. Restart Claude Code so the brain MCP server
   > picks up the new entry, then re-run `/aide:brain config` to seed the
   > entry-point artifacts into your brain.

   **Do not output the sync command for the user to run** â€” `/aide:brain config`
   completes wiring inside the slash-command session, never by handing the user
   a homework command.

### SEEDING flow â€” Step 5

5. **Seed the four entry-point artifacts into the brain via the brain MCP tools.**

   First verify the brain MCP write/list tools are available in this session
   (`mcp__brain__write_note`, `mcp__brain__list_directory`, etc.). If they are
   NOT available, the brain MCP server has not been loaded in this session. Emit
   this message verbatim and STOP:

   > The brain MCP server is not loaded in this session. Restart Claude Code,
   > then re-run `/aide:brain config` to seed the entry-point artifacts.

   **Never fall back to native filesystem tools** (Read, Write, Bash `ls`,
   Glob, etc.) to inspect or write the brain. The brain is a backend-agnostic
   abstraction; the filesystem is just one possible backing store. Other backends
   (hosted, Mem0, etc.) have no local filesystem at all. If the brain MCP tools
   are unreachable, the correct response is to STOP and ask the user to restart,
   never to improvise via the filesystem.

   When the brain MCP tools ARE available, for each artifact below: presence-check
   via `mcp__brain__list_directory` (or read tool) at the named path; if absent,
   write it via `mcp__brain__write_note` using the seed bytes from brain.aide's
   corresponding section (read via parseBrainAide's typed keys):
   - `playbookIndex` â†’ `coding-playbook/coding-playbook.md`
   - `studyPlaybook` â†’ `coding-playbook/study-playbook.md`
   - `updatePlaybook` â†’ `coding-playbook/update-playbook.md`
   - `researchIndex` â†’ `research/research.md`
   Skip any artifact that already exists (presence-only check â€” do not overwrite
   user-edited content).

   After the seeding loop completes, emit a brief completion summary naming
   each artifact and whether it was seeded or already present. Do not emit a
   restart message â€” the brain is fully wired and seeded; the user can now use
   `/aide` normally.

<!-- aide-config-end -->

